phase1.code:
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    int health = 75;
    int gold = 30;
    bool hasKey = false;

    // Simple if
    std::cout << "=== Health Check ===" << std::endl;
    if (health > 50) {
        std::cout << "You are healthy!" << std::endl;
    }

    // if-else
    std::cout << "\n=== Gold Check ===" << std::endl;
    if (gold >= 50) {
        std::cout << "You have enough gold to buy the sword!" << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "You need " << (50 - gold) << " more gold for the sword." << std::endl;
    }

    // if-else-if chain
    std::cout << "\n=== Key Check ===" << std::endl;
    if (hasKey) {
        std::cout << "You open the door with the key!" << std::endl;
    } else {
        std::cout << "The door is locked. You need a key." << std::endl;
    }

    // Nested if
    std::cout << "\n=== Treasure Room ===" << std::endl;
    bool hasSword = false;
    bool hasShield = false;

    if (hasSword) {
        if (hasShield) {
            std::cout << "You have both! You are fully equipped." << std::endl;
        } else {
            std::cout << "You have a sword but no shield." << std::endl;
        }
    } else {
        if (hasShield) {
            std::cout << "You have a shield but no sword." << std::endl;
        } else {
            std::cout << "You are completely unarmed!" << std::endl;
        }
    }

    return 0;
}

phase1.explanation:
🎮 **if/else is how games make decisions.**

Every game decision is an if statement:
- "If the player has enough health, they can fight"
- "If the player has the key, they can open the door"
- "If the player's level is high enough, they can equip the sword"

**Syntax:**
```cpp
if (condition) {
    // Code runs if condition is true
}

if (condition) {
    // Runs if true
} else {
    // Runs if false
}

if (condition1) {
    // Runs if condition1 is true
} else if (condition2) {
    // Runs if condition1 is false AND condition2 is true
} else {
    // Runs if all conditions are false
}
```

**Nested if:**
When you need to check multiple conditions that depend on each other.

**Common game uses:**
- Combat outcomes
- Quest completion checks
- NPC dialogue branches
- Level-up requirements

