#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int health = 30;

    // Missing semicolon after else
    if (health > 50) {
        std::cout << "Healthy!" << std::endl;
    }
    else 
        std::cout << "Not healthy!" << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

phase2.explanation:
The `else` has no matching `if` because the structure is broken.

**What went wrong:**
The `else` statement must be directly connected to an `if`. Here, the `if` block closed with `}`, and then `else` appears after it with a missing `{`.

**The fix:**
```cpp
if (health > 50) {
    std::cout << "Healthy!" << std::endl;
} else {
    std::cout << "Not healthy!" << std::endl;
}
```

**PlusPlus-chan says:**
"Indentation matters for readability, but for the compiler, braces matter more. Always use `{}` even for single statements. It prevents this error."

